WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:18.799
Thank you, Anne, for that intro. I appreciate it. As she mentioned, I'm an engineer at RStudio

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:23.959
and this is going to be an expanded version of the talk I gave at RStudio Conf so I can

00:00:23.959 --> 00:00:33.240
provide more detail on working with APIs in R. We will begin with an overview, a quick

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:39.520
review of the Web API basics, move on to tools for accessing those APIs. I have a couple

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:45.320
of examples prepared and a practical application that we have built in-house using these techniques.

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:50.980
And at the end, I'll give you some resources for finding out more information if you're

00:00:50.980 --> 00:00:58.380
interested in expanding your knowledge in this area. So API basics. There are a lot

00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:03.660
of data accessible over the Internet these days and a lot of it is made available via

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:09.019
APIs, which are application programming interfaces. These allow programs to talk to each other

00:01:09.019 --> 00:01:15.220
based on a communication contract. If you ask me a question in a way I understand, I

00:01:15.220 --> 00:01:21.180
will give you an answer. So there are two important parts to HTTP communication over

00:01:21.180 --> 00:01:26.500
the Web. There's the request, which is data sent to the server from the client, and then

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:32.059
the response, which is the data that the server sends back to that client. Now this is a very

00:01:32.059 --> 00:01:37.860
oversimplified view of the client-server communication, but the basics of it are ask a question and

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:42.180
get a response. And this is predicated on the fact that the client and server need to

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:48.300
understand each other's language, so to speak. The client can only send a request to the

00:01:48.300 --> 00:01:52.419
server that the server knows how to handle, and then the server will send that response

00:01:52.419 --> 00:01:55.940
back to the client, and the client will need to know how to parse that response to get

00:01:55.940 --> 00:02:02.779
the data out based on the question that was asked. Web APIs usually provide read and or

00:02:02.779 --> 00:02:08.139
write access to data stores when you're talking about Web APIs, and they allow you to access

00:02:08.179 --> 00:02:13.740
data on an ongoing basis. This is significant since it allows you to write scripts that

00:02:13.740 --> 00:02:20.020
pull an API to get the most up-to-date data. Not only will your analyses be current, but

00:02:20.020 --> 00:02:25.179
when the data changes, your scripts don't have to. Depending on how you design that

00:02:25.179 --> 00:02:29.300
script, data frames and plots will update automatically when your data changes without

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:35.660
you having to download a new CSV or import data manually. So as an example of this request

00:02:35.699 --> 00:02:43.259
response, I've put down here a curl request. Curl is a utility in the Unix world that allows

00:02:43.259 --> 00:02:50.220
you to make HTTP requests. In this case, I'm calling the OMDB API. This is the Online Movie

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:57.899
Database API, and I'm giving it a request with a query parameter, T for title and R for

00:02:57.899 --> 00:03:04.259
response format. So in this case, I'm saying, OMDB, give me the data for the title, the

00:03:04.259 --> 00:03:09.779
movie named Clue, and send it back to me in JSON format. The server understands this

00:03:09.779 --> 00:03:14.339
request because you've put it into the format that it expects, and so it sends a response

00:03:14.339 --> 00:03:19.539
that contains the data you asked for, the title, the year, the rating, et cetera. Again,

00:03:19.539 --> 00:03:24.899
this is a very simplistic example, but it gives you an idea of sort of how simple it

00:03:24.899 --> 00:03:29.380
is to ask a question and receive an answer and pull that data into the scripts that you're

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:37.940
writing every day. Web APIs are organized into resources that are often in a particular

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:43.179
hierarchy. In this example, there's a map that if you follow down from the top, you

00:03:43.179 --> 00:03:50.179
can get information about accounts, a particular account by its ID, the lists that a particular

00:03:50.179 --> 00:03:56.779
account has, the ID of those lists, the campaigns, the subscribers, the web forms, et cetera.

00:03:56.860 --> 00:04:01.259
So these are often organized in maps or webs of information, and if you know how to get

00:04:01.259 --> 00:04:06.419
to those different levels of information, you can construct a URL and ask for very specific

00:04:06.419 --> 00:04:11.979
things all the way down at the bottom, like clicks and tracked events in this case.

00:04:11.979 --> 00:04:17.140
Now that presumes that you understand a little bit about the API that you're trying to use.

00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:23.299
Fortunately, most of it has, many of them, I should say most of them, have decent documentation.

00:04:23.299 --> 00:04:28.739
This example is from the Star Wars API. So in this case, you can see across the left

00:04:28.739 --> 00:04:32.660
the kinds of information you can learn from this documentation. There's a getting started

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:38.019
guide here on the first page. But the things that you need to understand are the resources

00:04:38.019 --> 00:04:43.420
towards the bottom, so that you know what you can get and how to get it. For example,

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:47.899
this being the Star Wars API, you can get information about people, films, starships,

00:04:47.899 --> 00:04:52.899
planets, vehicles, et cetera. And the beauty of this documentation, this particular documentation

00:04:52.899 --> 00:04:58.019
is very good, so it'll tell you exactly what URL to use to get to that information, and

00:04:58.019 --> 00:05:03.619
it'll give you an example response as well. So it will tell you how to ask the question

00:05:03.619 --> 00:05:07.899
and what format the answer will be in, so that you can then parse it appropriately in

00:05:07.899 --> 00:05:13.299
your script.

00:05:13.299 --> 00:05:17.540
The important part here is that you need to learn that this, learn this API contract in

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:21.500
order to use it effectively. You need to know how to ask the question and how the answer

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:27.220
will be sent back to you. Fortunately, again, these documentation examples are often quite

00:05:27.220 --> 00:05:33.179
good, because they want you to be able to use it successfully as well.

00:05:33.179 --> 00:05:39.380
So to access these APIs and pull this information into R, you have a couple of different options.

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:43.500
In some cases, people have already written packages that will wrap those API calls for

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:50.260
a given service. The examples I've provided here are for AWS S3. This is S3 buckets in

00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:56.420
the Amazon Web Services universe. Our Google Analytics will get you information about Google

00:05:56.420 --> 00:06:03.299
Analytics based on the ID code that you have for your website. ACS is for the American

00:06:03.299 --> 00:06:07.940
Census information, et cetera. So some people have already wrapped these APIs into packages

00:06:07.940 --> 00:06:13.059
that are very easy to use. You do, I mean, if you can use them, by all means do. They

00:06:13.059 --> 00:06:16.739
make your life a lot easier. You do need to be aware that the people writing them may

00:06:16.739 --> 00:06:22.820
not have the same goals as you do. So they've written it to solve their problem and then

00:06:22.820 --> 00:06:26.700
made it public. But if you have other questions that you need to ask or if there's particular

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:31.140
end points that aren't covered in that package, you may need to write that yourself. Or there

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:34.660
could be no package for the data source that you're trying to reach, in which case you'll

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:41.820
write it yourself with some other tools. I recommend HTTR or Hitter for making the requests.

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:47.940
And then JSON Lite or XML2 for parsing the response. The most common response formats

00:06:47.940 --> 00:06:53.100
of API calls are JSON and XML, and these two packages are extremely good at parsing that

00:06:53.100 --> 00:07:03.179
data for you. Once you have the data in your script, you can wrangle the data the way that

00:07:03.179 --> 00:07:08.220
you normally do with data that comes in using the various packages in the tidyverse to get

00:07:08.220 --> 00:07:13.619
your data in an orderly rectangle so that you can use it for your analyses and for your

00:07:13.619 --> 00:07:21.260
plots. So Hitter request functions wrap HTTP verbs

00:07:21.260 --> 00:07:26.940
and fortunately they match them so they're very easy to figure out. Get is the one you'll

00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:30.380
probably be using the most commonly if you're interested in getting information from the

00:07:30.380 --> 00:07:37.339
web into your scripts. Post is to write back to a data store of some kind. Patch and put

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:42.940
are for updating. Delete is fairly obvious. And head is identical to get but without the

00:07:42.940 --> 00:07:46.859
body. So in this case you'd just be getting the metadata around the request without getting

00:07:46.859 --> 00:07:52.500
the body data. This can be useful as you're developing to understand sort of everything

00:07:52.500 --> 00:08:00.739
around the data itself in a much cheaper call. So to make a request, you first load Hitter

00:08:00.739 --> 00:08:05.739
with the library function, then call get with the URL. In this case I am using the Star

00:08:05.739 --> 00:08:11.100
Wars API. I'm calling planets with ID 1. So what I'm trying to do here is get information

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:17.100
about planet number 1 in the Star Wars API database. And this will give you a response

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:22.700
object. If you print that out, you get some really useful information. The actual URL

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:29.779
that was used after any redirects. The HTTP status. The file or content type. And the

00:08:29.779 --> 00:08:38.780
size of that response. And we'll talk a little bit more about how to use that later. So you

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:43.419
can use various helpers in Hitter to dig into the response object. For example, the status

00:08:43.419 --> 00:08:49.260
code helper will pull out just the code itself. 200 is what you want to see. That means okay,

00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:54.580
successful. Anything else may be a problem that you would need to handle in your code.

00:08:54.580 --> 00:08:59.020
Using the headers, helper will get you everything, all the metadata that came around through

00:08:59.020 --> 00:09:05.460
the header of the response. Date, content type, connection, transfer encoding, et cetera.

00:09:05.460 --> 00:09:11.260
There's quite a bit there. And then what most people are interested in is the body itself.

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:16.400
This is the content of the response. And so you would use the content function from Hitter

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:20.739
to pull that out. And here I'm just looking at the structure of it. So you can see that

00:09:20.739 --> 00:09:26.179
it is a list and the various amounts of data that come back. You'll see some of it is nested.

00:09:26.179 --> 00:09:29.619
Some of it is URLs. So you're going to need to understand all this in order to handle

00:09:29.619 --> 00:09:36.419
it appropriately in your scripts. So there are three main parts that you'll probably

00:09:36.419 --> 00:09:43.219
be most interested in in your HTTP response. The first is status. You can get the full

00:09:43.219 --> 00:09:49.099
status information with the HTTP status function. It will tell you everything that it possibly

00:09:49.099 --> 00:09:53.500
can about the status. In most cases, you're only interested in the code. So the status

00:09:53.500 --> 00:10:00.900
code, sorry, object, will come back with just the number that you can make decisions

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:05.179
in your code based on that number in most cases. You can automatically throw a warning

00:10:05.179 --> 00:10:10.059
or raise an error if a request does not succeed, if it was not 200, with the warn for status

00:10:10.059 --> 00:10:15.179
and stop for status helpers in the Hitter package. I highly recommend these. They convert

00:10:15.179 --> 00:10:20.900
HTTP errors into R errors, making them much easier to handle in your script. And they'll

00:10:20.900 --> 00:10:29.460
either warn or stop just as they imply. The second of the components that you'll want

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:35.179
to be interested in, that you'll want to handle are the headers themselves. Date, content

00:10:35.179 --> 00:10:39.780
type, connection, allow, things like that. There can be custom headers in here. It really

00:10:39.780 --> 00:10:44.679
depends on the API that you're working with. The one that you'll probably be using most

00:10:44.679 --> 00:10:49.780
often is the content type. Most APIs have a pretty consistent content type in their

00:10:49.780 --> 00:10:54.119
response. In this case, they're using JSON. So you may only have to worry about this once.

00:10:54.119 --> 00:10:58.179
But if you're calling an unfamiliar API or you're calling an API that changes frequently,

00:10:58.179 --> 00:11:01.460
it may behoove you to take a look at that content type to make sure that what you're

00:11:01.460 --> 00:11:08.299
parsing in your script matches what you're being sent. You can also get cookies, if you're

00:11:08.299 --> 00:11:13.900
interested. It really depends on your API or what you're trying to get out of it. But

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:18.059
the thing, again, that most people are interested in is the body. You use the content function

00:11:18.059 --> 00:11:26.739
in Hitter to get the response body. In this case, you pass it your object and a modifier.

00:11:26.739 --> 00:11:31.140
So in this case, I want a character vector. So I'm going to pass in the word text. And

00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:35.059
it'll give me back all of that information that we just saw earlier in the structure

00:11:35.059 --> 00:11:44.380
output. If you have non-text responses, you can get the raw content with the raw modifier.

00:11:44.380 --> 00:11:50.419
Or you can give it the parsed. Hitter has some default parsers for common file types,

00:11:50.419 --> 00:11:56.719
including JSON, XML, and a couple of others. This can be really useful if you want a quick

00:11:56.719 --> 00:12:03.260
and dirty look at it. But honestly, I tend to want to give the parser I want to do the

00:12:03.260 --> 00:12:08.059
parsing explicitly. And so I don't tend to use this very often. But it's there if you

00:12:08.059 --> 00:12:18.299
want it. So let's turn now to some examples. Here I've got some examples from the Star

00:12:18.299 --> 00:12:26.419
Wars universe. Let's see if I can make that a little bigger for you. Great. So I'm going

00:12:26.419 --> 00:12:29.900
to be working with the Star Wars API in these examples. And we're just going to walk through

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:35.539
some of the basics of how to deal with APIs in R. First thing I'm going to do is pull

00:12:35.539 --> 00:12:40.380
in Hitter JSON Lite, because I know that the response is going to be in JSON, and Regritter

00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:47.140
for piping to make it easier to read the code as I'm passing this data around. And our first

00:12:47.140 --> 00:12:53.559
goal is to get the data for the planet Alderaan. So the components of this request in Hitter

00:12:53.559 --> 00:12:59.419
are the same as they are in HTTP. You need a verb or a message, in this case get, a URL

00:12:59.419 --> 00:13:04.619
endpoint to hit, in this case we're looking for planets, and a parameter. Here we're going

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:09.820
to use search. Not all API endpoints need parameters, but in this case I'm explicitly

00:13:09.820 --> 00:13:16.659
going to do a search. And in this API, the key value pair is search and then your text

00:13:16.659 --> 00:13:24.099
that you want to search on. So if I run this, you'll see that the Hitter method get is in

00:13:24.099 --> 00:13:28.460
use. It's very straightforward. It's very readable. And I can take a look at that in

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:33.619
a second. But I also wanted to point out here that there's different ways to do your parameters.

00:13:33.619 --> 00:13:37.619
If you have many parameters, if you've got six parameters, this URL gets crazy long and

00:13:37.619 --> 00:13:41.719
hard to read. So there's another format you can use with the get method where you pass

00:13:41.719 --> 00:13:47.099
in a query list and you give it your key value pairs in that list. We don't need to do that

00:13:47.099 --> 00:13:52.179
here since I've only got one, but it's worth pointing out, especially if you're looking

00:13:52.179 --> 00:13:57.059
for a very detailed data that has a lot of parameters in the search query or in the set

00:13:57.059 --> 00:14:02.260
of parameters you're sending to the API. So now that I have that data, I'm going to take

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:10.460
a look at the data frame names. And I've got URL, status code, headers, cookies, the

00:14:10.460 --> 00:14:15.380
content itself, and the request and things like that. So I'm getting back a lot of information

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:19.820
from this API, which is great. I'm going to take a look specifically at the status code.

00:14:19.820 --> 00:14:24.059
This is a 200. Excellent. That means it's succeeded. And then I'm going to take a look

00:14:24.059 --> 00:14:29.659
at the headers, specifically the content type and its JSON, which is what we expect. Again,

00:14:29.659 --> 00:14:33.859
if you're looking at an API that you don't know very well, these fields can help you

00:14:33.859 --> 00:14:39.380
quite a bit in terms of deciding how to handle the data that comes back.

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:44.320
Now if I want the text of the response, I'm going to use the content method in Hitter.

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:49.539
Pass it the object I just created. Tell it to give me text and specify the encoding.

00:14:49.539 --> 00:14:53.580
Hitter will default to UTF-8, but it throws a little warning, so I usually just go ahead

00:14:53.580 --> 00:15:00.700
and put it in there explicitly. If you take a look at the resulting object, it's giving

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:07.059
you a count, a next, a previous, and the results themselves. And this is containing the data

00:15:07.059 --> 00:15:14.340
that you're interested for the most part. But it's not very easy to read, and it's not

00:15:14.340 --> 00:15:20.460
very easy to get that data back out. It's not very R formatted at the moment. So we're

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:26.260
going to need to parse this. You can do so with Hitter, as I mentioned earlier. So if

00:15:26.260 --> 00:15:33.020
you passed that into the content method with the parsed modifier here, you can. I'm going

00:15:33.020 --> 00:15:37.260
to go ahead and run that, and then I'll take a look at it. It's easier to read than this

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:45.179
is up here, but it's not necessarily easy to get to some of the information in the results

00:15:45.179 --> 00:15:50.440
themselves. So the count is pretty straightforward. And the results, if you take a look at the

00:15:50.440 --> 00:15:55.400
structure, it's what we would expect. It all looks fine. You've got some nested elements

00:15:55.400 --> 00:15:59.679
here under residents and films, and those are actual links to those, which makes it

00:15:59.679 --> 00:16:05.200
really, really easy to get that data programmatically. So it's all there, and it's all usable, and

00:16:05.200 --> 00:16:10.679
it's great. But in order to access this stuff, it's a little bit ugly in terms of this code.

00:16:10.679 --> 00:16:15.359
It's not the end of the world I've seen worse. But it's not always that easy to figure out

00:16:15.359 --> 00:16:21.280
kind of how that structure works. So I use JSON Lite to parse this instead of the JSON

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:26.520
Lite package. So I'm going to take that text content that we had up here. You can see that

00:16:26.520 --> 00:16:34.140
down here in the console. We have this. I'm going to pass that to the from JSON function

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:40.640
in JSON Lite. And what this is going to do, I just ran that code, and then we're going

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:45.440
to look at the object. It, again, gives you the count and the next and the previous, and

00:16:45.440 --> 00:16:50.039
we'll talk about that in a second. But the results are much easier to handle, in my opinion.

00:16:50.039 --> 00:17:00.760
They're certainly much easier to handle than this. So now that you've got that parsed in

00:17:00.760 --> 00:17:08.000
JSON content, I'm going to look specifically at the results and get the names. And now

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:13.400
it's a standard rectangular object that we can deal with a lot more easily. And when

00:17:13.400 --> 00:17:17.599
you want to pull that data out, this code is a lot easier to work with, a lot easier

00:17:17.599 --> 00:17:22.119
to read, in my opinion, than this code up here. So I do tend to use JSON Lite just to

00:17:22.119 --> 00:17:25.680
make my life easier and also to, you know, when I come back to this code in a couple

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:32.239
of months, I don't necessarily remember how I got that. But it's really easy to figure

00:17:32.239 --> 00:17:40.359
out how I got that. So JSON Lite, big fan. So I do this all the time. I do this every

00:17:40.359 --> 00:17:44.359
day, 43,000 times a day, and I don't want to rewrite the same code. So I wrote myself

00:17:44.359 --> 00:17:51.920
a little helper function here, and all it does is take the content function on the response,

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:56.760
tell it to bring out back the text encoded. If it's empty, warn. If it's not, run it through

00:17:56.760 --> 00:18:03.439
from JSON. So we can see how that looks here. In this case, I'm going to get all of the

00:18:03.439 --> 00:18:08.280
planets and stop for status. Again, we talked about that a little bit earlier. This is going

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:13.680
to stop the script if I get anything other than a 200. So I'll go ahead and run that,

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:24.920
I'll get all the planets, and then I'll JSON parse them. And now I have JSON planets. Again,

00:18:24.920 --> 00:18:29.839
we have a count, the next, the previous results. Every API is going to differ a little bit.

00:18:29.839 --> 00:18:34.040
In this case, this API is telling me how many results came back, or how many results are

00:18:34.040 --> 00:18:39.520
available, rather. That's the count. Next is going to be a link to the next page of

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:44.359
results. Previous is going to be the link to the previous page of results. And results

00:18:44.359 --> 00:18:50.479
is the data itself. So you'll notice here I'm going to run the JSON planets count, and

00:18:50.479 --> 00:18:55.800
there's 61 planets in this data set. But if you look at the length of the results that

00:18:55.800 --> 00:19:01.920
I just got back, it's only 10. This API pages, and that is not uncommon. You'll get your

00:19:01.920 --> 00:19:07.400
results back in pages rather than the whole shebang for performance reasons. You can imagine

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:10.959
asking an API to send you a million results. It's not going to want to give those to you

00:19:10.959 --> 00:19:17.880
all at once because it would take down their servers. So this API, like other APIs, does

00:19:17.880 --> 00:19:22.199
not do that. But you'll see if you look at the next object, it gives you the link for

00:19:22.199 --> 00:19:26.680
the next page. So in theory, you could page through these, get all of your results into

00:19:26.680 --> 00:19:31.839
a single data frame, and that's what we're going to do down here, actually. So that was

00:19:31.839 --> 00:19:37.280
the next page. I'm also going to take a look at the results themselves. So here I did the

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:42.800
JSON planets themselves, take a look at the results, and then get the names of the planets.

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:47.319
And so we'll get these first 10 planets that are in the database. So if I want to get the

00:19:47.319 --> 00:19:54.880
next page of results, it's really easy just to put the object itself as the target of

00:19:54.880 --> 00:20:00.439
the get function. Again, stopping for status. You don't even have to store it. All you have

00:20:00.439 --> 00:20:05.000
to do is just pass that in, and it will go get that next page at this URL that it already

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:14.239
has in that object. So if we run this, the next page will... Actually, I'm going to parse

00:20:14.239 --> 00:20:18.439
it as well. Excuse me. See, parse it, and then I'm going to take those results, get

00:20:18.439 --> 00:20:25.520
the name. This is the next 10 planets in the database. So now I've got the first page that

00:20:25.520 --> 00:20:30.640
is Swappy Planets, and now I've got the parsed next page that has the next set of pages,

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:35.719
the next set of data. So if your API results come back page like this, you can write a

00:20:35.719 --> 00:20:41.520
loop to follow the next URL until there are no more pages or bind all the data into a

00:20:41.520 --> 00:20:46.719
single data frame and have one big data frame full of all this data. It's not always what

00:20:46.719 --> 00:20:49.880
you want to do, but it's awfully convenient when you have small data sets. This is only

00:20:49.880 --> 00:20:55.520
61 planets, so there's no reason not to do that. Again, this will depend on the design

00:20:55.520 --> 00:20:59.959
of your API. Not all of them are quite this nice. Not all of them have those next and

00:20:59.959 --> 00:21:03.319
previous links the way this one does, but if it does, you may as well take advantage

00:21:03.319 --> 00:21:08.000
of it. So here I've written a little bit of code to grab all of the Star Wars planets

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:14.599
that are available. First, I'm going to get the first page of results, stop for status,

00:21:14.599 --> 00:21:19.000
parse them, and put them into an object that I'm going to call Swappy Planets, Star Wars

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:27.359
API planets, based on those results. Then the next page I am going to assign to the

00:21:27.359 --> 00:21:35.560
next object, and while that is not null, go get the next page, stop for status, parse,

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:42.040
and R bind it back into the Swappy Planets, then reset next page. This API is very nice.

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:47.040
If there is no next page, you'll get a null, which is why I'm able to do the is null. There

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:50.119
are other APIs that I've worked with that aren't quite this nice. They don't tell you

00:21:50.119 --> 00:21:55.079
when you're on the last page, and that can result in some more involved code than we're

00:21:55.079 --> 00:21:59.520
talking about here, but we're very lucky in this case. This API is quite nice in that

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:04.800
regard. Again, this all goes back to you needing to know your API very well before you start

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:10.400
writing a lot of this. But once you do, this code is only a couple of lines of code that

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:19.520
I've just run, and I've now got all 61 planets into one object. And I didn't have to do it

00:22:19.520 --> 00:22:24.640
by hand, and I didn't have to download a CSV and reimport it into R, and every single time

00:22:24.640 --> 00:22:29.280
I run this, it's going to give me the most up-to-date planets. If there are five more

00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:34.040
planets that get added between today and tomorrow, when I run this tomorrow, I will have 66 results

00:22:34.040 --> 00:22:40.959
and I can pipe that into whatever data script that I would like. So this has just been a

00:22:40.959 --> 00:22:47.599
very kind of simple example of how powerful these tools can be. In real life, as I mentioned

00:22:47.599 --> 00:22:53.280
earlier, you're going to have to handle some other cases. For example, if your paging API

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:59.119
doesn't tell you when it's on the last page. Errors that may get thrown. Headers, proxy,

00:22:59.119 --> 00:23:06.640
rate limits. Most times APIs have rate limits, so you can only call a given API a certain

00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:13.239
number of times per second or per minute or per hour, depending on the API. If you call

00:23:13.239 --> 00:23:16.520
any more than that, they'll throw an error, and that's just to keep people from overloading

00:23:16.520 --> 00:23:20.439
their servers. You're going to need to know how to handle that, if that happens within

00:23:20.439 --> 00:23:25.880
your script, and handle it appropriately so it doesn't crash your application. For more

00:23:25.880 --> 00:23:30.359
information on the functions that are available to help you with this sort of thing, you can

