So I touched upon some of these earlier. There are some other considerations. Again, you

00:29:42.660 --> 00:29:46.699
really need to know your API. You'll need to know what it expects and what it's going

00:29:46.699 --> 00:29:50.979
to send back to you. And you need to make sure that that documentation is honest. I

00:29:50.979 --> 00:29:56.020
know that developers make the best effort to make sure that those API documentation

00:29:56.020 --> 00:30:00.380
examples are accurate. But sometimes things change. Sometimes you happen to be looking

00:30:00.380 --> 00:30:05.180
at the wrong version. Sometimes there are mistakes. So you just want to experiment with

00:30:05.180 --> 00:30:09.699
it a little bit to figure out exactly how this is going to work. You do have to deal

00:30:09.699 --> 00:30:13.939
with paging, which we touched on a little bit, as well as rate limiting. Time to first

00:30:13.939 --> 00:30:18.619
bite is a little trickier. This is response time. So in some cases, APIs are not very

00:30:18.619 --> 00:30:24.020
fast. So you're going to have to figure out how to deal with that in your script and how

00:30:24.020 --> 00:30:28.339
to get around that, whether or not you need to wait for the response, things like that.

00:30:28.339 --> 00:30:32.660
You may need to handle data storage if you are putting this API information into another

00:30:32.660 --> 00:30:38.900
data store for you to analyze later. And it's a good idea to understand the hitter functionality

00:30:38.900 --> 00:30:44.500
that augments the things that we've already been talking about. So we did talk a bit about

00:30:44.500 --> 00:30:50.020
OF1 and OF2. You can also use proxies. And the authenticate method itself is a little

