So there's quite a bit in there. I would definitely recommend taking a look at the

00:31:39.859 --> 00:31:45.859
vignettes in the hitter package in the CRAN. And finally, I wanted to tell you a bit about

00:31:45.859 --> 00:31:50.339
a practical application. So this is what I work on every day. I spend a lot of time

00:31:50.339 --> 00:31:57.300
analyzing support tickets to identify product improvements, documentation enhancements,

00:31:57.300 --> 00:32:01.459
process improvements, things like that. I want to know how the user experience can

00:32:01.459 --> 00:32:06.660
form the improvements of our products. So I spend a lot of time in R crunching the data

00:32:07.219 --> 00:32:13.060
around support tickets. This application is in two parts. The first part is an R script

00:32:13.060 --> 00:32:18.739
that gets the support ticket data via API and puts it into an S3 bucket. And the second part

00:32:19.540 --> 00:32:25.380
is where various applications and reports pull that data from S3 and then run those analyses.

00:32:26.339 --> 00:32:34.020
So the reason I have this in two parts is because our support ticket tools API is quite slow.

00:32:34.739 --> 00:32:40.420
And I have to page through a lot of data. And to pull that into a single data frame the way that

00:32:40.420 --> 00:32:46.420
we did with that Star Wars API data takes a lot of effort. And it takes a lot of time because

00:32:46.420 --> 00:32:52.500
these API calls are not quick. So if I asked somebody who's loading an app or a report

00:32:52.579 --> 00:32:55.380
to sit there and wait for five minutes while that data comes back,

00:32:56.739 --> 00:33:00.900
they would close the window. They wouldn't do it. So in this case I have two different parts.

00:33:02.180 --> 00:33:08.979
And I've traded real-time access for application load time. In this case it doesn't really matter.

00:33:08.979 --> 00:33:13.699
What we're looking at here is historical trends. So we don't necessarily need real-time data.

00:33:13.699 --> 00:33:19.780
And so having this script run once a day even or five times a day and push that data into S3

00:33:20.500 --> 00:33:25.380
allows the application itself to just make one call to that S3 bucket and pull it back really

00:33:25.380 --> 00:33:31.219
quickly. So we've traded that off. Another alternate approach might be to make a series

00:33:31.219 --> 00:33:36.500
of incremental API calls that update the apps as the data comes in. But we didn't think that

00:33:36.500 --> 00:33:41.780
was necessary for this particular application which is why we have it in two parts. So the

00:33:41.780 --> 00:33:46.819
first part pulls that data, filters, tidies, flattens it using the tidyverse and saves it to

